metadata.name: Ordinary Places #203
metadata.description:
‚ÄúOrdinary Places‚Äù is a fully-coded meditation on the poetic beauty of everyday landscapes. 

The architectural characters in these landscapes include water towers (inspired by Bernd & Hilla Becher‚Äôs ‚ÄúWater Tower‚Äù photography series), gas stations (inspired by Ed Ruscha‚Äôs ‚Äú26 Gasoline Stations‚Äù photography book), and barns (inspired by childhood memories on my grandfather‚Äôs farm). 

Yet, while these scenes may seem ordinary upon first glance, something darker lurks beneath the surface. The hidden secrets of these Ordinary Places can only be revealed through the minting process. In this sense, the outputs are not merely a collection individual scenes, but instead, a coherent world animated by shared themes and narratives.     

Pressing the down arrow saves the coded output as a .png image.

metadata.name: Sketch F #48
metadata.description:
Sketch is an open-ended series. Works evolve as I code a generative project, sometimes drastically. Intermediate works usually don't see the light of day - they get archived and forgotten. This series is snapshots of different forms along the way - each standing alone, but also part of a larger meandering work flow. The word Sketch implies incompleteness. This project may end up being two works, or it could evolve for years. Part of the joy of generative art is never knowing what's around the corner. I have no set schedule. There may be multiple Sketches released a week, or it could be weeks or months between drops. I have no idea where Sketch is heading and there is no guarantee of cohesiveness from Sketch to Sketch. Color palettes and forms will change as new ideas are explored.

Sketch F(ree). A gift to all Sketch A-E collectors. The underlying grid structure from A-E remains, but more variation on size and distribution is added. Many more color palettes are introduced. Grid size, padding, and colors vary.

metadata.description:
A set of 2 359 296 particles follow the ebbs and flows of a digital spacetime field. 

Ruled by simple particle physics algorithms, this simulation allows to contemplate the similarities between stellar and neural dynamics, galactic and brain matters.

Each one of the 60 frames per second is a unique generative composition.

(Click ‚Äòopen‚Äô to see fullscreen, use wheel/pinch to zoom micro/macro )

-----
Technics

This experience is designed to be executed on a recent GPU (>2016) and displayed on 16/9 screens from FHD to 8K+ (1920x1080 ‚Üí 7680x4320) at 60FPS.

- JavaScript / ThreeJS / WebGL
- Unique generative animation
- Unlimited duration (no loop)
- 1 second to 3 minutes internal algorithm variations
- 5 equiprobable color palettes¬†: white, blue, light blue, green, gold

-----
Controls
Wheel/pinch¬†: zoom in/out to observe the phenomenon on different scales
Right click + drag¬†: move the observation area

metadata.name: St√∂rungen #218
metadata.description:
St√∂rungen is an exercise in suprematism in generative art. Not a new concept by any means, but (hopefully) uniquely applied.

In this work a single line is drawn from the center of the artwork, spiraling out and being perturbed by various constraints and disturbed by various controlling forces. These perturbations produce different illusions and, when combined, create feeling.

This piece is created in p5js, but is also intended to be plotted. Plotting will not allow for the blurring or color in the piece, but will instead give you a single color version of the perturbed spiral that you can print.

Open the token in a new window and:
- add &highres=true to the URL to get a highres image for printing
- add &svg=true to have the program create a plottable SVG
- double-click to download a PNG or SVG

metadata.name: GM.GEN.MATH #228
metadata.description:
Released on the occasion of the Tribute to Herbert W. Franke.
100% of the proceeds from primary sales are donated to the Foundation Herbert W. Franke. 
https://www.tribute-hwf.com/

~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

Undisputably, my mathematical background makes me naturally attracted to graphs, math functions, and transformations. I use math in ways that mathematicians could consider nonsense, but which produce fascinating aesthetic elements for creation (to paraphrase Herbert W. Franke). Combining scientific symbols and illustrations with fictional data produces pseudo-persuasive generative imagery that we can easily take to be absolute truth or in which we find meaningful patterns.
In the special issue of Leonardo, Visual Mathematics from 1992, Herbert W. Franke and Horst S. Helbig published the article Generative Mathematics: Mathematically Described and Calculated Visual Art.

They propose that ‚ÄúThrough the use of [mathematical] formulas (software) we gain generative principles. Beyond formal descriptions, we obtain guides for the construction of images. For example, if we use a parametric representation of a curve, the result is similar to traditional methods of drawing and painting [‚Ä¶]‚Äú Additionally, mathematics removes frame limits and adds the possibilities for transitions, transformations, movement, and interaction by implementing simple changes to the defining parameters.

I‚Äôm also very fond of the analysis and comparison (mentioned there) of digitally generated images and Constructivist design. Limitations of the technology (in the 70s) allowed only simple line drawings, based on fixed proportions same as Constructivists did. ‚ÄúIn a short time, all possible features were exhausted, so it became an obvious goal to try to extend them. This was done first by the use of random generators ‚Äî a highly interesting expansion of design principles [‚Ä¶]‚Äù Another expansion happened by adding curved shapes, first simple then complex that overcame possibilities of drawing with compasses and rulers. ‚Äú[‚Ä¶] oscillating curves are easily obtained through mathematical formulas and computer-graphic systems. The results we achieve on this basis do not look like Constructivist presentations, but their rationality and precision derive from Constructivist principles. ‚Äù

~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

Each mint contains both dark and light version, use D/N keys to switch between ‚Äúday & night‚Äù.
 
Base shapes are circles or Lissajous curves modified by the noise function. Shapes are arranged in a grid or by a circle packing algorithm. Lines are drawn smoothly or in stripes. Around 20% of the mints have lines in only one color (black/white). 

Depending on the browser/configuration rendering times will vary.

metadata.name: sewn gate #46
metadata.description:
Now what?
Warmth and comfort?

The lines create carpet patterns with different patterns and angles each time. Squares, rhombuses, plain embroidery and many others.
Why carpets?

They are very attractive with their comfort. A house or apartment with carpets always seems more residential and warm, no matter what kind of carpet. One color or pattern doesn't matter. It performs not only a design or warming function, but also a pleasant one for the soul. I hope I was able to make your day comfortable!

metadata.name: Wiggle #107
metadata.description:
Wiggle is a long-form generative collection of 1024 editions by Geoff Stearns that explores repetition using simple sine waves. There are 15 possible color palettes and the wave amplitude, complexity, and size are all variable.

The color palettes used in Wiggle are the same palettes used in Geoff's previous work, Hash Three Points (https://h3p.deconcept.com) and the projects share the same number of editions to invite collectors to find complimentary sets or pairs across the two projects.

https://twitter.com/tensafefrogs/status/1469491338714492929
